      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that's better. so when you say \"spooky action at a distance,\" is that just a metaphor physicists use to describe how weird the math is, or is there something actually \"spooky\" about the mechanics of it? like is there some kind of hidden process we're missing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was skeptical of the phenomenon because it seemed to violate the principle of locality, which states that objects are only directly influenced by their immediate surroundings. Einstein, along with physicist Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen, formulated the EPR paradox to highlight what they saw as a contradiction between quantum mechanics and the principles of classical physics. They argued that quantum mechanics must be incomplete because it allowed for instantaneous correlations between distant particles, which seemed to imply the existence of hidden variables that could explain these correlations without violating the speed of light limit.\n\nHowever, subsequent experiments, most notably those based on Bell's theorem and its inequalities, have shown that no local hidden variable theories can reproduce all the predictions of quantum mechanics. These experiments have consistently supported the quantum mechanical description of entanglement, suggesting that the \"spooky\" correlations are not due to any hidden process or information transfer at superluminal speeds but are instead a fundamental aspect of the nature of reality as described by quantum mechanics.\n\nIn essence, the \"spookiness\" refers to the counterintuitive nature of quantum mechanics and the challenge it poses to our classical understanding of the world. It is not that there is something actually",
      "source": "target",
